Figuring out PoE transformer wattage for 802.3bt Type 4 — what’s the right way to size it?I’m currently working on a PoE design targeting 802.3bt Type 4 (up to ~90W at the PSE side), and I realized pretty quickly that sizing the transformer isn’t as straightforward as just matching the headline power number.
At first I thought:
90W system → pick a ~90W transformer
But that assumption didn’t hold up once I started looking deeper into efficiency, losses, and real operating conditions.
What I understand about 802.3bt power levels
For Type 4, the system power can go up to ~90W at the source, but the actual available power at the device side is lower due to cable and conversion losses.
Typical numbers I’m working with:
~90W at PSE 
~70–75W usable at PD after losses (depending on cable length, efficiency, etc.) 
So already, the transformer is not just “90W rated” — it needs to handle more than what the load sees.
Where wattage sizing gets tricky
From what I’ve seen so far, transformer sizing depends on more than just output power:
1. Efficiency assumptions
If your DC/DC stage is, say, 90% efficient:
👉 Transformer needs to handle input power > output power
2. Thermal limits
In compact PoE designs (like IP cameras or access points), temperature rise becomes a constraint.
A transformer running close to its limit may pass electrically but fail thermally.
3. Topology matters
Depending on whether you're using:
Flyback 
Forward 
Active clamp 
The stress on the transformer changes quite a bit.
Push the same wattage through different topologies → different results.
4. Peak vs continuous power
PoE loads are not always constant.
Startup, inrush, or transient loads can exceed average power.
Rough way I’m approaching it (so far)
Instead of matching nominal wattage, I started thinking like this:
Target output power (e.g. 70W usable) 
Divide by efficiency (~0.9) → ~78W input 
Add margin (20–30%) 
👉 That puts transformer capability closer to ~95–110W range
Which is quite a bit higher than the “label” power.
Something that helped during evaluation
While looking at different transformer options, I noticed that some suppliers provide more than just basic specs.
For example, when I checked with VOOHU Electronics Technology Co., Ltd., what I found useful wasn’t just the wattage rating, but guidance around:
Recommended power derating under PoE conditions 
Thermal considerations in compact layouts 
Matching transformer behavior with specific topologies 
That kind of input made it easier to avoid under-sizing early in the design.
One thing I didn’t expect
I initially treated transformer wattage like a fixed number.
But it feels more like:
It’s a combination of thermal limit + core behavior + topology + efficiency
Not just a single rating.
